[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] uses a surrogate posterior and blatantly disregard this complexity.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Introduced by Hinton, this network is a hybrid of RBM and Sigmoid Belief Network.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The top 2 layers is an RBM and the second layer downwards form a sigmoid belief network.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] method and then throw away the recognition weights below the top RBM.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] As of 2009, 3-4 layers seems to be the optimal depth.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] These are early inspirations for the Variational Auto Encoders.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Its 2 networks combined into one—forward weights operates recognition and backward weights implements imagination.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] It is perhaps the first network to do both.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Helmholtz did not work in machine learning but he inspired the view of "statistical inference engine whose function is to infer probable causes of sensory input".
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] the stochastic binary neuron outputs a probability that its state is 0 or 1.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The data input is normally not considered a layer, but in the Helmholtz machine generation mode, the data layer receives input from the middle layer and has separate weights for this purpose, so it is considered a layer.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] These are inspired by Helmholtz machines and combines probability network with neural networks.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] An Autoencoder is a 3-layer CAM network, where the middle layer is supposed to be some internal representation of input patterns.
