[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The classical example of unsupervised learning in the study of neural networks is Donald Hebb's principle, that is, neurons that fire together wire together.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] In Hebbian learning, the connection is reinforced irrespective of an error, but is exclusively a function of the coincidence between action potentials between the two neurons.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] A similar version that modifies synaptic weights takes into account the time between the action potentials (spike-timing-dependent plasticity or STDP).
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Hebbian Learning has been hypothesized to underlie a range of cognitive functions, such as pattern recognition and experiential learning.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Among neural network models, the self-organizing map (SOM) and adaptive resonance theory (ART) are commonly used in unsupervised learning algorithms.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The SOM is a topographic organization in which nearby locations in the map represent inputs with similar properties.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The ART model allows the number of clusters to vary with problem size and lets the user control the degree of similarity between members of the same clusters by means of a user-defined constant called the vigilance parameter.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] ART networks are used for many pattern recognition tasks, such as automatic target recognition and seismic signal processing.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Two of the main methods used in unsupervised learning are principal component and cluster analysis.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Cluster analysis is used in unsupervised learning to group, or segment, datasets with shared attributes in order to extrapolate algorithmic relationships.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Cluster analysis is a branch of machine learning that groups the data that has not been labelled, classified or categorized.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Instead of responding to feedback, cluster analysis identifies commonalities in the data and reacts based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] This approach helps detect anomalous data points that do not fit into either group.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] A central application of unsupervised learning is in the field of density estimation in statistics, though unsupervised learning encompasses many other domains involving summarizing and explaining data features.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] It can be contrasted with supervised learning by saying that whereas supervised learning intends to infer a conditional probability distribution conditioned on the label of input data; unsupervised learning intends to infer an a priori probability distribution .
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Some of the most common algorithms used in unsupervised learning include: (1) Clustering, (2) Anomaly detection, (3) Approaches for learning latent variable models.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] One of the statistical approaches for unsupervised learning is the method of moments.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] In the method of moments, the unknown parameters (of interest) in the model are related to the moments of one or more random variables, and thus, these unknown parameters can be estimated given the moments.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The moments are usually estimated from samples empirically.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The basic moments are first and second order moments.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] For a random vector, the first order moment is the mean vector, and the second order moment is the covariance matrix (when the mean is zero).
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Higher order moments are usually represented using tensors which are the generalization of matrices to higher orders as multi-dimensional arrays.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] In particular, the method of moments is shown to be effective in learning the parameters of latent variable models.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] Latent variable models are statistical models where in addition to the observed variables, a set of latent variables also exists which is not observed.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] A highly practical example of latent variable models in machine learning is the topic modeling which is a statistical model for generating the words (observed variables) in the document based on the topic (latent variable) of the document.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] In the topic modeling, the words in the document are generated according to different statistical parameters when the topic of the document is changed.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] It is shown that method of moments (tensor decomposition techniques) consistently recover the parameters of a large class of latent variable models under some assumptions.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] The Expectation–maximization algorithm (EM) is also one of the most practical methods for learning latent variable models.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] However, it can get stuck in local optima, and it is not guaranteed that the algorithm will converge to the true unknown parameters of the model.
[src:variational-autoencoder/unsupervised-learning] In contrast, for the method of moments, the global convergence is guaranteed under some conditions.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] In machine learning, a **variational autoencoder** (**VAE**) is an artificial neural network architecture introduced by Diederik P.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] It is part of the families of probabilistic graphical models and variational Bayesian methods.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Thus, the encoder maps each point (such as an image) from a large complex dataset into a distribution within the latent space, rather than to a single point in that space.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The decoder has the opposite function, which is to map from the latent space to the input space, again according to a distribution (although in practice, noise is rarely added during the decoding stage).
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] By mapping a point to a distribution instead of a single point, the network can avoid overfitting the training data.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Both networks are typically trained together with the usage of the reparameterization trick, although the variance of the noise model can be learned separately.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Although this type of model was initially designed for unsupervised learning, its effectiveness has been proven for semi-supervised learning and supervised learning.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] A variational autoencoder is a generative model with a prior and noise distribution respectively.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Usually such models are trained using the expectation-maximization meta-algorithm (e.g. probabilistic PCA, (spike & slab) sparse coding).
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Such a scheme optimizes a lower bound of the data likelihood, which is usually computationally intractable, and in doing so requires the discovery of q-distributions, or variational posteriors.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] These q-distributions are normally parameterized for each individual data point in a separate optimization process.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] However, variational autoencoders use a neural network as an amortized approach to jointly optimize across data points.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] In that way, the same parameters are reused for multiple data points, which can result in massive memory savings.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The first neural network takes as input the data points themselves, and outputs parameters for the variational distribution.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] As it maps from a known input space to the low-dimensional latent space, it is called the encoder.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The decoder is the second neural network of this model.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] It is a function that maps from the latent space to the input space, e.g. as the means of the noise distribution.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] It is possible to use another neural network that maps to the variance, however this can be omitted for simplicity.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] In such a case, the variance can be optimized with gradient descent.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] To optimize this model, one needs to know two terms: the "reconstruction error", and the Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-D).
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Both terms are derived from the free energy expression of the probabilistic model, and therefore differ depending on the noise distribution and the assumed prior of the data, here referred to as p-distribution.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] For example, a standard VAE task such as IMAGENET is typically assumed to have a gaussianly distributed noise; however, tasks such as binarized MNIST require a Bernoulli noise.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The KL-D from the free energy expression maximizes the probability mass of the q-distribution that overlaps with the p-distribution, which unfortunately can result in mode-seeking behaviour.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The "reconstruction" term is the remainder of the free energy expression, and requires a sampling approximation to compute its expectation value.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] More recent approaches replace Kullback–Leibler divergence (KL-D) with various statistical distances, see "Statistical distance VAE variants" below.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] From the point of view of probabilistic modeling, one wants to maximize the likelihood of the data x by their chosen parameterized probability distribution $p_{\theta }(x)=p(x|\theta )$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] This distribution is usually chosen to be a Gaussian $N(x|\mu ,\sigma )$ which is parameterized by $\mu$ and $\sigma$ respectively, and as a member of the exponential family it is easy to work with as a noise distribution.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Simple distributions are easy enough to maximize, however distributions where a prior is assumed over the latents z results in intractable integrals.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Let us find $p_{\theta }(x)$ via marginalizing over z .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] where $p_{\theta }({x,z})$ represents the joint distribution under $p_{\theta }$ of the observable data x and its latent representation or encoding z .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] In the vanilla variational autoencoder, z is usually taken to be a finite-dimensional vector of real numbers, and $p_{\theta }({x|z})$ to be a Gaussian distribution.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Then $p_{\theta }(x)$ is a mixture of Gaussian distributions.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Unfortunately, the computation of $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ is expensive and in most cases intractable.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] with $\phi$ defined as the set of real values that parametrize q .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] This is sometimes called *amortized inference*, since by "investing" in finding a good $q_{\phi }$ , one can later infer z from x quickly without doing any integrals.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] In this way, the problem is to find a good probabilistic autoencoder, in which the conditional likelihood distribution $p_{\theta }(x|z)$ is computed by the *probabilistic decoder*, and the approximated posterior distribution $q_{\phi }(z|x)$ is computed by the *probabilistic encoder*.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Parametrize the encoder as $E_{\phi }$ , and the decoder as $D_{\theta }$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Like many deep learning approaches that use gradient-based optimization, VAEs require a differentiable loss function to update the network weights through backpropagation.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] For variational autoencoders, the idea is to jointly optimize the generative model parameters $\theta$ to reduce the reconstruction error between the input and the output, and $\phi$ to make $q_{\phi }({z|x})$ as close as possible to $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] As reconstruction loss, mean squared error and cross entropy are often used.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The Kullback–Leibler divergence $D_{KL}(q_{\phi }({z|x})\parallel p_{\theta }({z|x}))$ can be used as a loss function to squeeze $q_{\phi }({z|x})$ under $p_{\theta }(z|x)$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] That is, maximizing the log-likelihood of the observed data, and minimizing the divergence from the approximate posterior $q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ to the exact posterior $p_{\theta }(\cdot |x)$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] That is, we model the distribution of x conditional on z to be a Gaussian distribution centered on $D_{\theta }(z)$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] For a more detailed derivation and more interpretations of ELBO and its maximization, see its main page.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] To efficiently search for $\theta ^{*},\phi ^{*}={\underset {\theta ,\phi }{\operatorname {argmax} }}\,L_{\theta ,\phi }(x)$ the typical method is gradient descent.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The **reparameterization trick** (also known as stochastic backpropagation) bypasses this difficulty.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The most important example is when $z\sim q_{\phi }(\cdot |x)$ is normally distributed, as ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu _{\phi }(x),\Sigma _{\phi }(x))$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] This can be reparametrized by letting ${\boldsymbol {\varepsilon }}\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,{\boldsymbol {I}})$ be a "standard random number generator", and construct z as $z=\mu _{\phi }(x)+L_{\phi }(x)\epsilon$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Since we reparametrized z , we need to find $q_{\phi }(z|x)$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Let $q_{0}$ be the probability density function for $\epsilon$ , then $\ln q_{\phi }(z|x)=\ln q_{0}(\epsilon )-\ln |\det(\partial _{\epsilon }z)|$ where $\partial _{\epsilon }z$ is the Jacobian matrix of z with respect to $\epsilon$ .
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Many variational autoencoders applications and extensions have been used to adapt the architecture to other domains and improve its performance.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] $\beta$ -VAE is an implementation with a weighted Kullback–Leibler divergence term to automatically discover and interpret factorised latent representations.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] With this implementation, it is possible to force manifold disentanglement for $\beta$ values greater than one.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] This architecture can discover disentangled latent factors without supervision.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] The conditional VAE (CVAE), inserts label information in the latent space to force a deterministic constrained representation of the learned data.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Some structures directly deal with the quality of the generated samples or implement more than one latent space to further improve the representation learning.
[src:variational-autoencoder/variational-autoencoder] Some architectures mix VAE and generative adversarial networks to obtain hybrid models.
